<h2>Internal Process Of Component Source Code Framework Generation</h2>
    <p>When using emake&nbsp;hello.car command, emake.bat receives the parameter "hello.car", it finds that this is a CAR file, then it executes gen_src series command.</p>
    <p>gen_src including the following commands: </p>
    <ul>
    <li><pre class="code">
carc -c hello.cls hello.car
</pre>
    <p>This command generates corresponding compressed resource library hello.cls under current directory according to hello.car. Here mentioned resource library is definition that provides interface, class, method, struct, enumeration.</p>
    <li><pre class="code">
cls2src -f hello.cls
</pre>
    <p>This command generates corresponding source code framework according to information provided by hello.cls, which is CHello.h, CHello.cpp, sources here.</p>
    <li><pre class="code">
if exist hello.cls del /f hello.cls
</pre>
    <p>This command deletes all temporary hello.cls from the current working directory during compilation. So when emake&nbsp;hello.car command finishes executing, you cannot see hello.cls in current directory using dir command but the generated source code CHello.h,CHello.cpp, sources and original hello.car file.</p>
    </ul>
    <p>The following code is in the generated CHello.h file: </p>
    <pre class="code">
#include "_CHello.h"

class CHello : public _CHello
{
	бнбн
}
</pre>
    <p>We can see that class CHello inherits _CHello class.This class is defined in _CHello.h header file. Actually _CHello.h does not exist. In the compilation phase that follows, _CHello.h is first generated and therefore CHello.h can be compiled and correctly executed.</p>

